{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "626c9b41",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Number of Circuits: Why it matters"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a60c5392",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We explore why running the same circuit several times, and increasing the number of those repetitions is beneficial, even when running circuits with a [large number of shots](precision_vs_shots.ipynb)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us state explicitly that the number of circuits is defined here as repetitions of the same circuit such as\n",
    "\n",
    "`backend.run([circ]*100, shots=backend.configuration().max_shots)` \n",
    "\n",
    "where the circuit in question is repeated 100 times, as an example. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3491f388",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Load modules, account and backend"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from qiskit import *\n",
    "\n",
    "#Hellinger Fidelity for comparing different count distributions\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import hellinger_fidelity\n",
    "\n",
    "# For plotting\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "plt.style.use('ibmq-dark')\n",
    "%config InlineBackend.figure_format='retina'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "IBMQ.load_account();\n",
    "provider = IBMQ.get_provider(group='deployed')\n",
    "backend = provider.backend.ibm_cairo"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Explore maximum number of experiments (circuits)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us list all the attributes of `backend.configuration()` ..."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "dict_keys(['n_uchannels', 'u_channel_lo', 'meas_levels', 'qubit_lo_range', 'meas_lo_range', 'meas_kernels', 'discriminators', 'hamiltonian', 'rep_times', 'dt', 'dtm', 'channels', '_qubit_channel_map', '_channel_qubit_map', '_control_channels', 'acquisition_latency', 'conditional_latency', 'meas_map', '_data', 'backend_name', 'backend_version', 'n_qubits', 'basis_gates', 'gates', 'local', 'simulator', 'conditional', 'open_pulse', 'memory', 'max_shots', 'coupling_map', 'supported_instructions', 'dynamic_reprate_enabled', 'rep_delay_range', 'default_rep_delay', 'max_experiments', 'sample_name', 'n_registers', 'credits_required', 'online_date', 'description', 'processor_type', 'parametric_pulses'])"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 3,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "backend.configuration().__dict__.keys()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "... to find that that the relevant attribute here is `max_experiments`, which has recently been increased to up to 300 "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "300"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "backend.configuration().max_experiments"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fc88d19d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Alternatively using the new class of backends [`BackendV2`](https://qiskit.org/documentation/stubs/qiskit.providers.BackendV2.html), `max_experiments` is a direct attribute of this class. At this time, access to backends using `BackendV2` is managed by qiskit-ibm-provider, which you may install by running \n",
    "```\n",
    "git clone https://github.com/Qiskit/qiskit-ibm-provider.git\n",
    "cd qiskit-ibm-provider\n",
    "pip install .\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "4975cfe3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit_ibm_provider import IBMProvider\n",
    "provider2 = IBMProvider()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "fd163ede",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "version = 2 , maximum number of circuits = 300\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "backend2=provider2.backend.ibm_cairo\n",
    "print(\"version =\",backend2.version,\", maximum number of circuits =\",backend2.max_experiments)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Exemplary experiment"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In a recent [post on dynamical decoupling](../how-to/dynamical_decoupling/dynamical_decoupling.ipynb) we compared the performance of different approaches. We do use 100.000 shots in this example. Here, we analyze the significance of using a suitable number of circuits as well. Instead of re-running the example, we show here how to load previously run jobs from the same provider, based on job tags:  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "jobs = backend.jobs(limit=7,job_tags=[\"dynamical decoupling\"])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The names of the different decoupling sequences were encoded in tags as well:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "['no_dd', 'XY8pm', 'XY4pm', 'X2pm', 'XY8', 'XY4', 'X2']"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 8,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "jobtags=[thisjob.tags() for thisjob in jobs]\n",
    "for tags in jobtags:\n",
    "    tags.remove('dynamical decoupling')\n",
    "sequences=list(np.concatenate(jobtags).flat)\n",
    "sequences"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "jobsdict=dict(zip(sequences,jobs))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In order to compare the distribution of counts, we run the circuit used to create the [results we just loaded](../how-to/dynamical_decoupling/dynamical_decoupling.ipynb) in a simulation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 658.679x325.08 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 10,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 277,
       "width": 547
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "circ = QuantumCircuit(4)\n",
    "circ.h(0)\n",
    "circ.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "circ.cx(1, 2)\n",
    "circ.cx(2, 3)\n",
    "circ.measure_all()\n",
    "circ.draw()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sim_job = provider.backend.ibmq_qasm_simulator.run(circ)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sim_counts = sim_job.result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We are now in position to compare the counts obtained from simulation to each entry in the retrieved jobs. We do this by means of the [Hellinger Fidelity](https://qiskit.org/documentation/stubs/qiskit.quantum_info.hellinger_fidelity.html)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fidelities_all = dict(zip(sequences,range(len(sequences))))\n",
    "for sequence in jobsdict:\n",
    "    fidelities_all[sequence]=list(\n",
    "        map(lambda x: hellinger_fidelity(sim_counts,x),\n",
    "        jobsdict[sequence].result().get_counts()))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This allows us to plot the resulting Fidelities"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 29,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 501,
       "width": 636
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sorted_sequence = ['X2','XY4','XY8','X2pm','XY4pm','XY8pm','no_dd']\n",
    "fig = plt.figure()\n",
    "ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])\n",
    "for sequence in sorted_sequence:\n",
    "    ax.plot([sequence]*100,fidelities_all[sequence],'o')\n",
    "ax.set_title('Hellinger fidelities of dd sequences, 100 circuits at 100.000 shots each \\n')\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([min(min(fidelities_all.values()))*0.999,max(max(fidelities_all.values()))*1.001])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One observation that is relevant here: Despite running each circuit at 100.000 shots each, we do see a small, yet non-negligible deviation of the result from each individual circuit (i.e. each individual dot in the plot). So it is necessary to sample this distribution for each different sequence here, or reduce the deviation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Low number of circuits may lead to wrong conclusions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For illustration, we show the \"extreme\" case of using just a single circuit to prove a point may lead to wrong conclusions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "bad_case_fidelities = [min(fidelities_all['X2']),max(fidelities_all['XY4']),min(fidelities_all['XY8']),min(fidelities_all['X2pm']),\n",
    "max(fidelities_all['XY4pm']),max(fidelities_all['XY8pm']),max(fidelities_all['no_dd'])]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "bad_case = dict(zip(sorted_sequence,bad_case_fidelities))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 501,
       "width": 628
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig = plt.figure()\n",
    "ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])\n",
    "ax.bar(*zip(*bad_case.items()))\n",
    "ax.set_title('BAD SAMPLING! (1 circuit only) \\n Hellinger fidelities of Dynamical Decoupling sequences')\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([min(bad_case_fidelities)*0.999, max(bad_case_fidelities)*1.001])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So after running just one circuit, here it looks as if the best strategy was \"no_dd\", i.e. to apply no dynamical decoupling at all. It also looks as if the sequences \"X2pm\" and \"XY4pm\" perform equally well. Compare this to the full plot above using 100 circuits to see that this conclusion drawn after running a single circuit for each is not justified."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Scaling behaviour due to higher number of circuits"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us look more qualitatively at why running many circuits can help to draw the right conclusions. We select the best approach presented (\"X2pm\" sequence) and analyze how the mean value and standard deviations evolve over the number of circuits."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "averages=[]\n",
    "std_devs=[]\n",
    "for i in range(1,len(fidelities_all['X2pm'])):\n",
    "    averages.append(np.mean(fidelities_all['X2pm'][:i]))\n",
    "    std_devs.append(np.std(fidelities_all['X2pm'][:i]))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 33,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 519,
       "width": 697
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig=plt.figure()\n",
    "ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])\n",
    "ax.set_title('Sampling by running jobs with several circuits: \\n effect on Hellinger Fidelity (X2pm sequence)')\n",
    "ax.plot(fidelities_all['X2pm'],'o',label='individual results per circuit')\n",
    "ax.plot(np.add(averages,std_devs),label='mean value + standard deviation')\n",
    "ax.plot(averages,label='mean value (moving average)')\n",
    "ax.plot(np.subtract(averages,std_devs),label='mean value - standard deviation')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Number of circuits')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Fidelity')\n",
    "ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.1, 1))\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We observe that even when averaging over the results, there is still significant variance for a small number of circuits. As the number of circuits increases, the mean Fidelity stabilizes. We can confirm this observation by comparing the evolution of each mean Fidelity over the number of circuits, for each of the different approaches."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "averages_dict={}\n",
    "for sequence in sorted_sequence:\n",
    "    averages_dict[sequence]=[]\n",
    "\n",
    "    for i in range(1,52): \n",
    "        averages_dict[sequence].append(np.mean(fidelities_all[sequence][:i]))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 500,
       "width": 741
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig = plt.figure()\n",
    "ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])\n",
    "for sequence in [n for n in sequences if n != 'XY8pm']:\n",
    "    ax.plot(averages_dict[sequence],label=sequence)\n",
    "ax.set_title('mean Hellinger fidelities of dd sequences vs number of circuits')\n",
    "ax.set_ylim([0.894,max(max(averages_dict.values()))*1.001])\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Number of circuits')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Fidelity')\n",
    "fig.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.175, 1))\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Again, the fluctuations in the mean value naturally smooth out with more circuits. For the sequences \"X2\" and \"XY4pm\" it is quite notable that there is no clear trend of better performance until about 20 circuits are run for each approach."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we consider how the accumulation of shots influences the advantages from averaging. Ideally, running the same circuit several times simply adds up the number of shots from each run."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 45,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cumulative_counts = [(i+2)*(10**5) for i in range(len(averages))]\n",
    "cumulative_std_dev = list(map(lambda x: 1/np.sqrt(x),cumulative_counts))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 519,
       "width": 901
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig=plt.figure()\n",
    "ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])\n",
    "ax.set_title('Sampling by running jobs with several circuits: \\n effect on Hellinger Fidelity (X2pm sequence)')\n",
    "ax.plot(fidelities_all['X2pm'],'o',label='individual results per circuit')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.plot(averages + 1/np.sqrt(10**5),'.',label='mean + standard deviation \\n (from No. shots per circuit)')\n",
    "ax.plot(np.add(averages,cumulative_std_dev),'-',label='mean + standard deviation \\n (from cumulative No. shots)')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.plot(averages,label='mean value (moving average)')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.plot(np.subtract(averages,cumulative_std_dev),'-',label='mean - standard deviation \\n (from cumulative No. shots)')\n",
    "ax.plot(averages - 1/np.sqrt(10**5),'.',label='mean - standard deviation \\n (from No. shots per circuit)')\n",
    "\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Number of circuits')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Fidelity')\n",
    "ax.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.02, 0.75))\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The dotted lines present bounds in Fidelity for each individual run, while the solid lines close to the mean represent the increasingly narrow standard deviation from averaging over the cumulative counts."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In Conclusion, it becomes obvious that a larger number of circuits helps in obtaining precise and correct results."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 48,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

     "data": {
